  "description": [
    "36 PROTESTS REPORT ON CHILD LABOR I g In Letter to Secretary Davis Editor Challenges Accuracy of Bureau Figures i By the Associated Press CHARLOTTE X C September 28 Characterizing as a tricky and un derhand showing of statistics the recent announcement of figures of the childrens bureau of the Depart ment of Labor showing more than 35 per cent increase in child labor since the annulment of the federal 0 child labor law David Clark pub lisher of the Southern Textile Bul letin made public a letter of pro test which he had written to Sec retary Davis of the Department of Labor Objects to Comparison Mr Clark pointed out that Hhe periods selected for comparison were the firt sis months of 1922 when there was unemployment and Idleness 1 in almost every industrial section and the first six months of 1933 J which composed a period of unusual industrial activity and declares that there is no evidence that there was a greater increase in the cm ployment of young people of fourteen to sixteen years of age than of older persons nor is there any evidence that there was any employment in violation of state laws or outside"
